{"parse":{"title":"macaroni","pageid":83560,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Macaroni closeup.jpg|thumb|A pile of elbow macaroni]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|maccaroni}}\n* {{sense|pasta}} {{alter|en|maccheroni|mac}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{bor|en|it|maccaroni|pos=plural of {{m|it|maccarone|ng=archaic variant of {{m|it|maccheroni||[[fool]]}}}}}}, of uncertain origin. Variously derived from late {{der|en|gkm|μακαρία||[[food]] [[made]] from [[barley]]}}, from {{der|en|grc|μάκαρ||[[blessed]]; [[favored]] by the [[gods]]}}, or from {{m|it|maccare|ng=archaic variant of {{m|it|ammaccare||to [[bruise]]; to [[crush]]}}}}, from {{der|en|la|macco|maccāre}} of the same meaning. Compare {{cog|scn|maccarruni||a single piece of macaroni}}.\n* As a fop, apparently from the British {{w|Macaroni Club}} rather than from Italian use of {{m|it|maccarone}} for fools and bumpkins.\n* As a former form of currency, used to calque {{der|en|es|macuquino|ng=18th-century colonial slang for a similarly clipped coin}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/mæk.əˈɹəʊ.ni/|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-macaroni.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{enPR|măk'ə-rōʹnē|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/ˌmæk.əˈɹoʊ.ni/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊni|s=4}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~|s|es}}\n\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A [[type]] of [[pasta]] in the [[form]] of [[short]] [[tube]]s, [[typically]] [[boil]]ed and [[serve]]d in [[soup]], with a [[sauce]], or in [[melt]]ed [[cheese]]; a [[dish]] of this. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}\n#: {{hypo|en|elbow macaroni|pipe macaroni}}\n#* '''1778''', Hannah Glasse, ''The Art of Cookery...'', new ed., p. 124:\n#*: Take half a pound of small pipe-'''macaroni'''.\n#* {{RQ:Landon Romance|page=32|volume=III|passage=\"I can recommend this '''macaroni''', for it is my favourite dish: I am very national. You will not take any? Ah, young ladies are, or ought to be, light eaters. Your ladyship will, I trust, set your fair companion an example.\"}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|obsolete|or|informal|loosely}} [[pasta|Pasta]], {{n-g|particularly}} [[thick]]er [[noodle]]s, [[spaghetti]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:pasta}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1673|author=John Ray|title=Observations...|page=405\n|passage=[[pasta|Paste]] made into strings like pack-thread or thongs of whit-leather (which if greater they call '''Macaroni''', if lesser [[vermicelli|Vermicelli]]) they cut in pieces and put in their pots as we do [[oatmeal|oat-meal]] to make their menestra or broth of.}}\n#* '''1883''', ''Encyclopaedia Britannica'', 9th ed., Vol. XV, [[:s:Encyclopædia Britannica, Ninth Edition/Macaroni|s.v.]]:\n#*: '''MACARONI'''... is a preparation of wheat originally peculiar to Italy, in which country it is an article of food of national importance. The same substance in different forms is also known as [[vermicelli]], pasta or Italian pastes, [[taglioni]], [[fanti]], [[&c.]]\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|obsolete}} {{synonym of|en|gnocchi|gloss=[[Italian]] [[dumpling]] made of [[potato]] or [[semolina]]}}. {{defdate|17th c.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1611|author=John Florio|title=Queen Anna's New World of Words|section=s.v\n|passage='''Maccaróni''', a kind of [[meat]] made of round [[pieces|peeces]] of [[pasta|paste]], [[boiled|boyled]] in water and put into a dish with butter, spice and grated-cheese [[upon|vpon]] them.}}\n#* {{RQ:Jonson Cynthia's Revels|act=II|scene=iii|page=203|passage=He doth learne to make ſtrange ſauces, to eat ''[[anchovy|ænchouies]]'', '''''maccaroni''''', ''[[bovoli|bouoli]]'', ''[[fagioli]]'', and ''[[caviare|cauiare]]'', becauſe hee loues ’hem; {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|chiefly|historical|and|pejorative}} A [[dandy]] or [[fop]], {{n-g|particularly}} in the 18th [[century]] a [[young]] [[Englishman]] who had [[travel]]led in [[Europe]] and [[subsequently]] [[dress]]ed and [[spoke]] in an [[ostentatiously]] [[affected]] [[Continental]] [[manner]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}\n#: {{syn|en|cockscomb|popinjay|poseur|Thesaurus:dandy}}\n#* '''1764''' February 6, Horace Walpole, letter to the Earl of Hertford:\n#*: ... the '''Maccaroni''' Club (which is composed of all the travelled young men who wear long curls and spying-glasses) ...\n#* '''1764''' May 27, Horace Walpole, letter to the Earl of Hertford:\n#*: Lady Falkener's daughter is to be married to a young rich Mr. Crewe, a '''Macarone'''...\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1770|month=June|title=Oxford Magazine|page=228\n|passage=There is indeed a kind of animal, neither male nor female, a thing of the neuter gender, lately started up amongst us. It is called a '''Macaroni'''. It talks without meaning, it smiles without pleasantry, it eats without appetite, it rides without exercise, it wenches without passion.}}\n#* '''1773''', Robert Hitchcock, ''The '''Macaroni''''', Act I:\n#*: I wanted you to be a man of spirit; your ambition was to appear a first-rate '''Macaroni'''; you are returned fully qualified, and determined, I see, to [[shew]] the world what a contemptible creature an English-man dwindles into, when he adopts the follies and vices of other nations.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1777|author=w:Richard Brinsley Sheridan|title=The School for Scandal|section=II.ii\n|passage='Sure never were seen two such beautiful Ponies;<br>Other Horses are Clowns—and these '''macaronies'''}}\n#* {{RQ:Wilde Dorian Gray|text=Delicate lace ruffles fell over the lean yellow hands that were so overladen with rings. He had been a '''macaroni''' of the eighteenth century, and the friend, in his youth, of Lord Ferrars.|XI}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1997|author=w:Thomas Pynchon|title=Mason & Dixon\n|passage=A small, noisy party of Fops, '''Macaronis''', or [[lunarian|Lunarians]],—it is difficult quite to distinguish which,—has been working its way up the street.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|Caribbean|now|historical|numismatics}} A 19th-[[century]] [[quarter]]-[[silver dollar]] [[coin]], {{n-g|typically}} a [[full]] 2-[[real]] [[coin]] or a [[quarter]] [[clipping]] of an 8-[[real]] [[coin]] from [[Central America|Central]] or [[South America]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1808|author=John Stewart|title=An Account of Jamaica...|page=59\n|passage=The silver coins are [[silver dollar|dollars]] (6[[shilling|s.]] 8[[penny|d.]]), half dollars, and quarter dollars, or '''maccaronies''' as they are here popularly called.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|zoology}} {{ellipsis of|en|macaroni penguin}} (''[[Eudyptes chrysolophus#Translingual|Eudyptes chrysolophus]]''). {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=May 16 1955|journal=The Times|page=5\n|passage=15 penguins were hatched and reared in the Edinburgh Zoo—seven kings, four [[gentoo]]s, three '''maccaronis''', and one ringed.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|ethnic slur}} {{synonym of|en|Italian|gloss=a [[person]] from [[Italy]] or of [[Italian]] [[ethnicity]]}}. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* '''1845''' December 15, Frances Anne Kemble, letter:\n#*: Surely I shall always be able, go where I will, among [[frogs]] or '''maccaronis''', to procure [[sucre noir]], or [[inchiostro nero]].\n# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete}} {{ellipsis of|en|macaroni tool}}. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1867|author=George Alfred Rogers|title=The Art of Wood Carving|page=12\n|passage=Now take the '''maccaroni''' and cut away the wood on either side of the vein...}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|Scottish|zoology|obsolete}} {{synonym of|en|lizard canary}}. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1876|author=Robert Linlithgow Wallace|title=The Canary Book|page=165\n|passage=Lizards are known among Scotchmen as ‘'''macaronies'''’.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|literature|obsolete}} A [[mix]] of [[language]]s in [[macaronic]] [[verse]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1884|author=James Edwin Thorold Rogers|title=Six Centuries of Work and Wages|volume=I|page=166\n|passage=... political songs in Latin or in a '''maccaroni''' of Latin and English ...}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|Australia|slang}} [[nonsense|Nonsense]]; [[meaningless]] [[talk]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:nonsense}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1924|author=D. H. Lawrence; et al|title=The Boy in the Bush|page=46\n|passage=Yes. [[jam|Jam]], '''macaroni''', [[cockadoodle]]. We're plain people out [[hereaways]], not mantle ornaments.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|beefaroni|stuffaroni\n|beefaroni\n|macaroni wheat\n|elbow macaroni\n|holy macaroni\n|macaroni and cheese\n|mac and cheesy\n|pipe macaroni\n|macaroni cheese\n|macaroni penguin\n|tenderoni\n|Chinese macaroni\n|macaroni and gravy\n|macaroni pie\n|macaroni salad\n|macaronian\n|macaroni intelligencer\n|monkeyrony\n|macaroni train\n|macaroni shrug\n|macaronism\n|macaroni dress\n|macaroni fiddle\n|macaroni cane\n|macaroni gin\n|macaroni soup\n|macaroni philosopher\n|macaroni stall\n|macaroni stake\n|macaroni tool\n|macaroni marquis\n|macaroni pudding\n|macaronyish\n|macaroni dealer\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|macaronic}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|ja|マカロニ|tr=makaroni|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|마카로니|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ms|-|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|ms|ماکاروني|sclang=1|sc=ms-Arab}}\n** {{desc|ms|makaroni|sclang=1}}\n* {{desc|gd|macaroni|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|type of pasta}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|مَكَرُونَة|f}}, {{t+|ar|مَعْكَرُونَة|f}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|մակարոն}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|通心粉|tr=tung1 sam1 fan2}}, {{t|yue|通粉|tr=tung1 fan2}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|通心粉|tr=tōngxīnfěn}}, {{t|cmn|通心麵|tr=tōngxīnmiàn}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|makaróny|m-p}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|macaroni}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|makaronid|p}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|makaroni}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|macaronis|m-p}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მაკარონი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Makkaroni|p}}\n* Greek: {{t|el|κοφτό μακαρονάκι|n}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|makaróni}}, {{t+|hu|csőtészta}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|makaroni}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|maccheroni|m-p}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|マカロニ|tr=makaroni}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|마카로니}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|collȳra|f}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|makaroni}}, {{t|ms|laksa geronggang}} {{q|archaic}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|imqarrun}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|मॅकारोनी|m}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|makaroni}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|ماکارونی|tr=mâkâroni}}, {{t|fa|نی‌رشته|tr=neyrešte}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|[[rurka|rurki]]|nv-p}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|macarrão|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|макаро́ны|f-p}}, {{t+|ru|рожок|alt=рожки́|m-p}} {{qualifier|one type}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|macaroni|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|макароне|f-p}}\n*: Latin: {{t|sh|makarone|f-p}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|maccarruna|m-p}}\n* Southern Altai: {{t|alt|макарон}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|macarrones|m-p}}, {{t+|es|macarrón|m}}, {{t|es|codito|m}} {{qualifier|Latin America}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|makaroner|p}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|makarna}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|макаро́ни|f-p}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t|vi|macarôni}}, {{t|vi|mì ống}}, {{t|vi|mì ống cong}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|מאַקאַראָנען|p}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# {{lb|en|historical}} [[chic|Chic]], [[fashionable]], [[stylish]]; in the manner of a macaroni.\n\n====See also====\n* [[w:macaroni|Wikipedia article on macaroni (pasta)]]\n* [[w:macaroni_(fashion)|Wikipedia article on macaronies]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{bor|en|fr|macaron}}. {{doublet|en|macaron}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/mak.əˈɹəʊ.ni/|a=UK}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-macaroni.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{enPR|măk'ə-rōʹnē|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/ˌmækəˈɹoʊni/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊni|s=4}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[macaroon]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1777|author=Charlotte Mason|title=The lady's assistant for regulating and supplying her table: being a complete system of cookery, containing one hundred and fifty select bills of fare, properly disposed for family dinners ... with upwards of fifty bills of fare for suppers ... and several desserts: including likewise, the fullest and choicest receipts of various kinds ...|genre=cooking|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=14IEAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22paste%22+Italy+(%22macaroni%22+OR+%22maccheroni%22+OR+%22spaghetti%22)&source=gbs_navlinks_s|page=300|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=14IEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA300&dq=%22paste%22+Italy+(%22macaroni%22+OR+%22maccheroni%22+OR+%22spaghetti%22)&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xvtPT_m7IKadiAe5i53oCw&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=biscuit&f=false|passage='''Macaroni'''. It comes from Italy. It is a biscuit made of almonds, eggs, flower, and sugar.}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aacimnor|Marciano|Marocain|armoniac|armonica|marocain}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:OED Online|macaroni|n}}\n\n{{C|en|Pasta}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|nl|it|maccaroni}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/ˌmaː.kaːˈroː.ni/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-macaroni.ogg}}\n* {{rhyme|nl|s=4|oːni}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nl-noun|m|-|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|macaroni}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|nl\n|macaronischotel\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|bor=1|id|makaroni}}\n\n{{C|nl|Pasta}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|fr|it|maccaroni}}, obsolete variant of {{m|it|maccheroni||macaroni}}, plural of {{m|it|maccherone}}, of uncertain origin.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Benoît Prieur-macaroni.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Saint-Maurice-de-Beynost>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-macaroni.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n[[File:Cornettes3.jpg|thumb|des '''macaroni'''s]]\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|usually|in the plural}} {{l|en|macaroni}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|macaroni chinois}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|pl|makaron|bor=1}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|fr|Marocain}}, {{l|fr|marocain}}\n\n{{C|fr|Foods}}\n\n==Scottish Gaelic==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|gd|en|macaroni}}, from {{der|gd|it|maccheroni}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{gd-noun|g=m}}\n\n# [[#English|macaroni]]\n\n===Mutation===\n{{gd-mut-cons|m|acaroni}}\n\n{{C|gd|Pasta}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|macaroni}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|es|pingüino macaroni}}"}}